  "market_context": "Intraday session following London manipulation; price swept prior lows, formed a bullish breaker block (low-high-lower low-higher high), then closed above it, triggering reaccumulation in the breaker zone as mitigation for upward continuation.",
  "key_observation": "The analyst identified a breaker block pattern (low-high-lower low-higher high) on ES and ETH charts, which after being closed over, acted as support (mitigation) for a higher move.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Analyst observed an aggressive downward move (manipulation) followed by a strong upward displacement that broke a prior high, shifting structure to the upside.",
    "Step 2: Analyst marked the sequence 'low-high-lower low-higher high' as a breaker block, noting it functions as a mitigation block when price closes above it.",
    "Step 3: Analyst confirmed price retested the breaker block zone and used it as support to continue higher, validating it as a reaccumulation area.",
    "Step 4: Analyst contrasted this with dragging old up-close candles (bearish OBs) forward as mitigation zones, emphasizing breaker blocks are a specific form of mitigation."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price continued higher after retesting the breaker block, taking out the original consolidation range; trade was a successful long entry at the breaker mitigation zone.",
  "lessons": "Breaker blocks—when closed over—serve as high-probability mitigation/reaccumulation zones. They are not just structural markers but actionable PD arrays for continuation entries aligned with the new market structure.",
